'''Susannah Constantine''' (born [[June 3]], [[1962]]<ref name="rootsweb"/> in [[London]]) is an award-winning [[England|English]] fashion guru, fashion and style advisor, television personality, [[television presenter|presenter]] and bestselling fashion [[author]]. She is best-known as the co-host, along with [[Trinny Woodall]], on the [[BBC]] style series ''[[What Not to Wear]]''. Following her success on the show, she went on to co-host ''[[Trinny & Susannah Undress]]'' amongst making appearances as a style advisor on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]''. Her earlier career consisted of working for several well-known designers such as [[John Galliano]].

She has co-written many fashion advice book with Woodall, some of which have become bestsellers in the United Kingdom and [[United States]]. Her second book, entitled ''What Not to Wear'', has won her a prestigious British Book Award<ref name="Award"> ''[http://www.britishbookawards.co.uk/bba/pnbb_previouswinners.asp British Book Awards]'' &mdash; britishbookawards.co.uk. Retrieved [[February 22]], [[2007]].</ref> and has sold 670,000 copies.<ref name="Booksales"> ''[http://parkinson.tangozebra.com/guest.phtml?guest_id=93 Parkinson]'' &mdash; parkinson.tangozebra.com. Retrieved [[March 8]], 2007.</ref> It is estimated that her various style advice books have sold 2.5 million copies in Britain and the United States.<ref name="2.5million"> ''[http://www.pr.com/press-release/24689 Trinny and Susannah Have Launched the Official TrinnyAndSusannah.com Website]'' &mdash; pr.com. Retrieved [[April 11]], [[2007]].</ref>

==Education==
Constantine was privately educated at boarding schools including Queens Gate School in [[South Kensington]], London<ref name="therapists"/> and the £20,000-per-year [[St Mary's School, Wantage|St Mary's School]] in [[Wantage]], [[Oxfordshire]] which was run by [[nun]]s.<ref name="oldschool"> ''[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/news.html?in_article_id=468490&in_page_id=1770 What not to say to your old school, by Susannah]'' &mdash; dailymail.co.uk. Retrieved [[July 15]], [[2007]].</ref> Her time at St Mary's School was described by herself as "miserable" due to her homesickness and insecurity, meaning she was not able to make friends.<ref name="oldschool"/> 

In mid 2007, Constantine spoke about how she received a letter from St Mary's School, inviting her to come back to the school to talk about her career and success to current pupils. Constantine immediately declined the offer with a four-letter refusal and wrote "No fucking way" on the letter she had received.<ref>''[http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/article.html?in_article_id=58502&in_page_id=7 Susannah tells nuns 'No f***ing way']'' &mdash; metro.co.uk. Retrieved [[August 28]], [[2007]].</ref> Her personal assistant was then left to deal with it, who wrongly sent the inviting letter with the hand-written sentence by Constantine, back to the school. The boarding school then wrote a shocked letter back, explaining that they will not let Constantine near the school again.<ref name="therapists"/><ref name="oldschool"/>

==Early career==
Constantine originally did a year of [[montessori]] training after she had left school but she then moved onto other projects.<ref name="therapists"/> She is best-known as a fashion guru and style advisor, where her fashion career started when she worked for many years under fashion designer [[Giorgio Armani]] as a shop girl in America.<ref name="Partner"> ''[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20000405/ai_n14298169  Me And My Partner: Trinny Woodall and Susannah Constantine]'' &mdash; independent.co.uk. Retrieved from findarticles.com [[April 13]], [[2007]].</ref> She later came back to London and worked for designers such as [[Alistair Blair]] and [[John Galliano]] and gained an even greater understanding of fashion.<ref name="Partner"/> Constantine had previously taught children for three years<ref name="Partner"/> and has also worked as a style consultant for [[Harrods]].<ref name="therapists"> ''[http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/fashion/article2050017.ece Retail therapists (Pages 1, 2 & 3)]'' &mdash; timesonline.co.uk. Retrieved [[July 16]], [[2007]].</ref><ref name="Swells"> ''[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/comment/story/0,6903,864290,00.html Just a couple of swells]'' &mdash; observer.guardian.co.uk. Retrieved [[March 11]], [[2007]].</ref> She then started working with the [[British Brain and Spine Foundation]] and consequently met the sports editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. Whilst doing a piece for ''[[GMTV]]'', he asked Constantine to report the women's World Cup Final in [[cricket]] on finding out that it was her passion. She proceeded to write about cars and then fashion.

She teamed up in [[1994]] with [[Trinny Woodall]] after they had met at a party hosted by [[David, Viscount Linley]].<ref name="Swells"/> They proceeded to write ''Ready to Wear'', a weekly style guide for ''The Daily Telegraph'' which ran successfully for seven years.<ref name="Swells"/> The column promoted affordable high-street fashion and they used themselves to illustrate which clothing suited which figure.<ref name="therapists"/> Constantine and Woodall were also co-founders of [[Ready2shop.com]], a [[dot-com]] fashion advice business that ceased trading after running out of funding in November [[2000]]. After the business venture had failed, investors lost a reputed £10 million.<ref name="10million">''[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2002/12/21/ntrin21.xml No, seriously . . . does my cheque look big in this?]'' &mdash; telegraph.co.uk. Retrieved [[March 8]], [[2007]].</ref> 

Constantine made her television debut when [[Granada Sky Broadcasting]] signed her and Woodall to present a daytime shopping show named after their column in the ''Daily Telegraph'' called ''Ready to Wear'' and soon released their first fashion advice book. The book was unsuccessful and resulted in the pulping of 13,000 copies of the book.<ref>''[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml;jsessionid=VYHPUF0QJIOX3QFIQMGSFFWAVCBQWIV0?xml=/news/2002/12/18/ntrin18.xml Fashion 'makeover queens' land £1m book deal]'' &mdash; telegraph.co.uk. Retrieved [[May 7]], [[2007]].</ref> Soon after the start of their television career, they secured a frequent makeover slot on the show ''[[Richard & Judy]]''. It ensured that they had further exposure in television and gained attention from [[Jane Root]], controller of BBC Two, who took a risk and signed them up after their book ''Ready to Dress'' and their internet business Ready2shop.com had been unsuccessful.<ref name="Swells" />

==Television==
===Style advisor===
Constantine is well-known and was made famous for co-hosting ''[[What Not to Wear]]'' with Trinny Woodall, which required using her fashion advice, expertise, and brutally honest remarks in order to reform participants' appearances and fashion style. Constantine has commented in an interview that "anyone can achieve style. It doesn't matter who you are or where you're from."<ref name="mia"> ''[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20020908/ai_n12578387/pg_1 Mammary mia!]'' &mdash; sundayherald.co.uk. Retrieved from findarticles.com [[August 18]], [[2007]].</ref> Constantine also says that she finds dressing other women easy, but finds it difficult when dressing herself.<ref name="deceivingappearances"> ''[http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/spectrum.cfm?id=1414982004 Deceiving appearances]'' &mdash; scotsman.com. Retrieved [[June 1]], [[2007]].</ref> She co-hosted ''What Not to Wear'' from [[2001]] to [[2005]] where she was often noted for her tactile behaviour with the candidates. A notorious moment arose when she spontaneously pulled a female candidate's underwear down during filming as her knicker line was visible.<ref name="deceivingappearances" /> The show made Constantine and Woodall household names and are now known together as [[Trinny and Susannah]]. 

During her time co-hosting ''What Not to Wear'' for five series, she and Woodall gained recognition for their work on the show, winning a [[Royal Television Society#Awards|Royal Television Society Award]] in 2002 for being the best factual presenters.<ref>''[http://www.rts.org.uk/awards_det.asp?id=1457&sec_id=336 Royal Television Society]'' &mdash; rts.org.uk. Retrieved [[February 14]], [[2007]].</ref> In 2002, Constantine provided [[Jeremy Clarkson]] with a makeover on a celebrity version of ''What Not to Wear'',<ref>''[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2003/02_february/01/tvmoments_2002.shtml BBC One honours the best TV moments from 2002]'' &mdash; bbc.co.uk. Retrieved [[March 6]], [[2007]].</ref> and later did a spin-off show called ''What Not to Wear on the Red Carpet'' in which she transformed the appearances of [[Jo Brand]] and [[Sophie Raworth]] for a [[BAFTA Award]] ceremony. After Clarkson appeared on the show, he stated "I'd rather eat my own hair than shop with these two [Constantine and Woodall] again".<ref name="mia"/> ''What Not to Wear'' also gained her international fame when it was aired in countries such as Spain, America and Portugal.

Constantine and Woodall became the faces of [[Nescafé]] in 2003. They were featured in television advertisements promoting the brand of coffee and were contracted to give a Nescafé competition winner a £10, 000 makeover.<ref>''[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4159/is_20060409/ai_n16185407 NESCAF: Trinny and Susannah take us al for mugs]'' &mdash; independent.co.uk. Retrieved from findarticles.com [[July 25]], [[2007]].</ref> In 2005, Constantine was a guest on the live BBC coverage of [[Wedding of Charles, Prince of Wales and Camilla Parker Bowles|The Royal Wedding of Charles and Camilla]], where she contributed as a fashion and contemporary social commentator.<ref>''[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/03_march/30/wedding.shtml The Royal Wedding: Charles and Camilla]'' &mdash; BBC Press Office. Retrieved [[February 16]], [[2007]].</ref> 

Constantine defected from the BBC to [[ITV]] for a deal worth a reputed £1.2 million,<ref>''[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/showbiz/showbiznews.html?in_article_id=412181&in_page_id=1773 Susannah's shock at husband's plastic surgery suggestion]'' &mdash; dailymail.co.uk. Retrieved [[June 25]], [[2007]].</ref> where she started a new show, ''[[Trinny & Susannah Undress]]'' on [[October 3]], [[2006]]. The second series aired on ITV in June 2007. The first two series saw Constantine advising couples who were finding problems within their marriage. The advice and fashion makeover provided, aimed to make the troubled relationships stronger. Constantine stated in an interview that the show was very emotionally draining, and as a result, she often went home crying.<ref name="therapists"/> The programme did not come without its critics who questioned the depth at which Constantine and Woodall could deal with serious issues raised during the programme.<ref name="therapists"/> Their straight-talking advice however, ensured that they were voted the ninth most terrifying celebrities on television in a 2006 ''[[Radio Times]]'' poll consisting of 3, 000 people.<ref>''[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/showbiz/showbiznews.html?in_article_id=410712&in_page_id=1766&in_page_id=1766&expand=true#StartComments Ramsay is scariest TV celebrity]'' &mdash; dailymail.co.uk. Retrieved [[August 27]], [[2007]].</ref> The third series will see a change in format and will explore why British people can be "badly dressed".<ref>''[http://www.merrymedia.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3081&Itemid=196 ITV1 Undress the Nation]'' &mdash; merrymedia.co.uk. Retrieved [[August 5]], [[2007]].</ref> Since the transfer to ITV, ''What Not to Wear'' on [[BBC One]] has been hosted by [[Lisa Butcher]] and [[Mica Paris]]. 

''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' has also seen her appearing regularly as a makeover and style expert, where she gave fashion advice and guidelines on how to better overall appearances and figures. The show also saw Constantine and Woodall giving numerous American citizens fashion makeovers.<ref>''[http://www.oprah.com/tows/pastshows/200405/tows_past_20040518.jhtml ''The Oprah Winfrey Show'', What Not to Wear this summer]'' &mdash; oprah.com. Retrieved [[February 13]], [[2007]].</ref>

===Guest appearances===
For charity, in 2002 during the BBC's [[Children in Need]] programme, both Constantine and Woodall performed their own version of [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s hit single "[[Vogue (song)|Vogue]]" with a group of celebrity backing singers.<ref>''[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/10_october/24/cin2002.shtml The Big Night on BBC Television]'' &mdash; bbc.co.uk. Retrieved [[August 18]], [[2007]].</ref> She appeared again on Children in Need in 2004, which saw a special segment with her giving the fictional ''[[EastEnders]]'' characters [[Little Mo]] and [[Mo Harris]] a makeover à la ''What Not to Wear'', commenting on them in her usual style.<ref>''[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2004/11_november/09/cin.shtml Children In Need 2004]'' &mdash; bbc.co.uk. Retrieved [[February 16]], [[2007]].</ref> She has also appeared on ''[[Comic Relief]]: Red Nose Night Live 05''.

In 2005, Constantine voiced a robot version of herself in the [[science fiction]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. In the episode "[[Bad Wolf]]" in [[2005]], Trine-e and Zu-Zana were two robots acting out a deadly futuristic version of ''What not to Wear'', offering makeovers in a more gruesome form.<ref>''[http://www.thesun.co.uk/article/0,,2001320029-2006170431,00.html Dr Who is TV medicine]'' &mdash; thesun.co.uk. Retrieved [[August 18]], [[2007]].</ref>

Constantine has appeared three times on ''[[Parkinson (TV series)|Parkinson]]'' and made appearances on ''[[This Morning (TV series)|This Morning]]'' and [[Star in a Reasonably-Priced Car]] which is a recurring segment on the [[BBC Two]] motoring programme ''[[Top Gear (current format)|Top Gear]]'', amongst numerous other talk shows. In [[2003]], when Constantine and Woodall were interviewed on ''[[Parkinson (TV series)|Parkinson]]'',  actress [[Meg Ryan]] had a controversial interview with [[Michael Parkinson]], which resulted in negative publicity for Ryan. Parkinson said that he felt Ryan's behaviour to his fellow guests Woodall and Constantine, whom she turned her back on, was "unforgivable".<ref>''[http://business.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=598&id=521652006 Parky was a 'nut', says Meg Ryan]'' &mdash; scotsman.com. Retrieved [[January 26]], [[2007]].</ref>

==Beyond television==
To coincide with Constantine's move from the BBC to ITV1 in 2006, she co-launched an underwear range called "Trinny and Susannah Magic Pants" which are made of [[Nylon]], produced to flatten the [[tummy]], [[buttocks]] and [[thighs]] so that the areas appear slimmer and compact.<ref>''[http://www.mailonsunday.co.uk/pages/live/femail/article.html?in_article_id=407513&in_page_id=1879 Trinny and Susannah show what not to underwear]'' &mdash; mailonsunday.co.uk. Retrieved [[May 14]], [[2007]].</ref> Constantine even wore them after giving birth to her third child.<ref>''[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2003/10_october/24/parky_251003.shtml Meg Ryan talks to Parkinson]'' &mdash; bbc.co.uk. Retrieved [[February 15]], [[2007]].</ref> She also became the face of [[Littlewoods Shop Direct Group|Littlewoods Direct]] with Woodall, as during its sponsorship of their new ITV1 programme ''Trinny & Susannah Undress'' in 2006, orders rose by thirty per cent. From [[January 2007]], the pair produced a twelve page fashion advice section within the Littlewoods catalogue and made a booklet called ''The Golden Rules'', which was distributed to all Littlewoods customers with fashion advice to suit a range of body shapes. 

They have also produced online guidelines for Littlewoods, where customers are able to key in body measurements and get advice on clothing according to their figure.<ref>''[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/consumer_goods/article1288827.ece Littlewoods signs up Trinny and Susannah]'' &mdash; timesonline.co.uk. Retrieved [[February 22]], [[2007]].</ref> Constantine and Woodall made their first appearance in television advertisements to promote Littlewoods in [[April 2007]].<ref>''[http://www.marketingweek.co.uk/cgi-bin/item.cgi?id=55875&d=pg_dtl_art_news&h=0&f=0 Trinny and Susannah to front Littlewoods TV ads]'' &mdash; marketingweek.co.uk. Retrieved [[April 19]], [[2007]].</ref> The ''[[Mission: Impossible (film)|Mission:Impossible]]''-themed advertisements feature Constantine and Woodall as themselves dressed as two agents trying to rob a Littlewoods designer warehouse.  

She and Trinny Woodall have recently launched their own Littlewoods range which consists of trousers, coats and tops which, like their underwear range, are designed to shrink the buttocks, reduce thighs or flatten tummies. The range is currently available exclusively at Littlewoods Direct.<ref name="therapists"/> She currently co-writes a weekly column for ''[[The Sun (newspaper)|The Sun]]''.[[Image:TrinnyandSusannahWNTW.jpg|200px|right|Constantine (right) on book cover]] 

===Books===
Constantine has co-written several style advice books with her fashion partner Trinny Woodall, some of which  include ''What Not to Wear'', ''What You Wear Can Change Your Life'' and ''Trinny & Susannah Take on America'' and have sold a reputed 2.5 million books worldwide.<ref name="2.5million"/> The fashion advice books have been number one bestsellers in Britain and the United States, appearing on both [[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times bestseller list]]<ref>''[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sitesearch.do?query=the+sunday+times+bestsellers+-+trinny+and+susannah&hitsperpage=10&nextOffset=0&offset=0&leftStartIndex=1&leftEndIndex=10&submitStatus=searchFormSubmitted&mode=simple&sectionId=987 Search results for Trinny and Susannah bestsellers]'' &mdash; timesonline.co.uk. Retrieved [[May 30]], [[2007]].</ref> and [[New York Times Best Seller list|The New York Times bestseller list]],<ref>''[http://query.nytimes.com/search/query?query=Trinny+Woodall&srchst=nyt&d=nytdsection%2b&o=e%2b&v=Books%2b&c=a%2b&sort=newest&n=10&dp=0&daterange=full&frow=0 Trinny and Susannah bestsellers]'' &mdash; nytimes.com. Retrieved [[May 30]], [[2007]].</ref> and have been translated throughout the world.<ref>''[http://www.itv.com/page.asp?partid=6606 Trinny and Susannah Undress]'' &mdash; itv.com. Retrieved [[January 26]], [[2007]].</ref>

Other success with their books includes winning a [[British Book Awards|British Book Award]] for their book ''What Not to Wear'' in 2003 for the TV & Film Book of the Year.<ref name="Award"/> The book was at one point selling 45,000 copies each week and sold 300,000 copies in just fifteen weeks.<ref>''[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article806573.ece Nothing suceeds like success]'' &mdash; timesonline.co.uk. Retrieved [[May 30]], 2007.</ref> Total sales reached 670,000 copies, consequently outselling [[Jamie Oliver]] and [[Nigella Lawson]].<ref name="Booksales"/> It was also reported that Constantine and Woodall secured a £1 million book deal to write more of their fashion books.<ref>''[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/student/article805020.ece The makeover millionaires]'' &mdash; timesonline.co.uk. Retrieved [[February 22]], [[2007]].</ref> Her next book, ''The Body Shop Bible'', is due to be published in September 2007.

==Personal life==
Constantine grew up in an old priory in the [[Leicestershire]] village of [[Knipton]] and went hunting from the age of seven.<ref name="Interview"> ''[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/femail/article.html?in_article_id=229872&in_page_id=1879 Acne, alcohol … and non-stop sex]'' &mdash; dailymail.co.uk. Retrieved [[March 17]], [[2007]].</ref> She was close with her father, Joseph Constantine, who was successful in the property and shipping sectors, was an [[Eton College|ex-Eton]] pupil and served in the [[Coldstream Guards]]. When she was young, Constantine would rely on her father for fashion advice and has commented that any style that she has, she learned from him. He was a talented artist and was offered worldwide art exhibitions, although too modest to accept. His death came suddenly and was a landmark for Constantine.<ref name="deceivingappearances" />

Constantine became a fixture in [[1980s]] British gossip columns and newspapers as the result of her relationship with [[Princess Margaret of the United Kingdom|Princess Margaret]]'s son, [[David, Viscount Linley]] which lasted for eight years.<ref>''[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2002/12/18/ntrin18.xml Fashion 'makeover queens' land £1m book deal]'' &mdash; telegraph.co.uk. Retrieved [[May 7]], [[2007]].</ref> Princess Margaret thought well of Constantine and even called her "my daughter-in-law".<ref name="Interview"/> She has also had a relationship with Pakistan cricket captain [[Imran Khan]] but is now married to Danish entrepreneur and businessman Sten Bertelsen, who launched Death cigarettes,<ref name="scrubbing"/> and has three children with him called Joe, Esme and CeCe.<ref name="therapists"/><ref name="Swells" /> They have recently bought a 120-acre property in [[Sussex]].<ref name="therapists"/>

After having her first child, Constantine suffered from severe [[postnatal depression]]<ref name="Interview"/> and panic attacks.<ref name="scrubbing"> ''[http://www.guardian.co.uk/Archive/Article/0,4273,3962942,00.html 'They wanted to give us a good scrubbing']'' &mdash; guardian.co.uk. Retrieved [[August 28]], [[2007]].</ref> Upon discovering that she was pregnant for a third time, as well as being overcome with delight, she felt despair as it came at a time when best friend Trinny Woodall was struggling to conceive and undergoing [[IVF]] treatment. Constantine's pregnancy was unplanned and unexpected whilst Woodall was struggling to conceive. In an interview Constantine said that she "couldn't bear to tell her." A short time later however, Woodall became pregnant with her first child.<ref name="Interview"/>

In 2002, when on a visit to [[Cannes film festival]], Constantine and Woodall were the targets of gem thieves. The thieves broke into the villa on the [[French Riviera]] where they were staying, rendered Constantine and Woodall unconscious with [[chloroform]], and then continued to steal money and jewellery.<ref>''[http://news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=336&id=576012002 TV duo drugged and robbed]'' &mdash; scotsman.com. Retrieved [[June 20]], [[2007]].</ref> [[Carol Vorderman]] was involved in a feud with Constantine and Woodall in 2003. Vorderman commented harshly about the double-act, after they had called her an "overdone Eighties nightmare" and named Vorderman in their list of the 20 worst-dressed celebrities.<ref>''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/showbiz/2800439.stm Carol Vorderman launches fashion attack]'' &mdash; news.bbc.co.uk. Retrieved [[February 17]], [[2007]].</ref>

==In popular culture==
On the show ''[[Big Impression]]'', impressionists [[Alistair McGowan]] and [[Ronni Ancona]] took to spoofing her presenting techniques on ''What Not to Wear'',<ref name="10million" /> just one of the shows in which Constantine's character has been spoofed. She has also been referred to on the comedy sketch show ''[[French & Saunders]]'' as being a "bully" in a Celebrity Grading Report, where [[Dawn French]] was a headmaster of a celebrity school and had to write comments on various celebrities. Similarly, Constantine and Trinny Woodall were featured in a cartoon strip in the comic ''[[Viz (comics)|Viz]]'' where they were portrayed as school bullies who targeted victims who wore [[NHS]] glasses and hand-me-down clothing.<ref>''[http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/review.cfm?id=940912004 Notes from the knicker drawer]'' &mdash; scotlandonsunday.com. Retrieved [[July 25]], [[2007]].</ref> When Constantine and Woodall saw the cartoon strip, they threatened to take legal action against the comic.<ref>''[http://www.thesun.co.uk/article/0,,4-2002580357,00.html Trinny and Sue]'' &mdash; thesun.co.uk. Retrieved [[February 3]], [[2007]].</ref>

She was also spoofed in a sketch on ''[[2DTV]]'' when it featured her giving [[Santa Claus]] a makeover, substituting his traditional red suit for a casual shirt and trousers.<ref>''[http://www.mirror.co.uk/catchall/tm_method=full%26objectid=12469674%26siteid=89520-name_page.html What to wear if you want to make a big impression]'' &mdash; mirror.co.uk. Retrieved [[March 15]], [[2007]].</ref> She was also portrayed as a lesbian with Woodall on [[Avid Merrion]]'s show ''[[Bo' Selecta!]]''. Even though she was lampooned on the show, Constantine took the portrayal as a compliment.<ref>''[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_200504/ai_n13508408/pg_2 We can't stop touching women's boobs]'' &mdash; dailymail.co.uk. Retrieved from findarticles.com [[April 13]], [[2007]].</ref> In 2006, on [[Gordon Ramsay]]'s ''[[The F-Word]]'', Ramsay named his two pigs Trinny and Susannah after Constantine and Woodall.<ref>''[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2006/07_july/06/42_kendal.shtml The Kumars at No 42 returns to BBC ONE]'' &mdash; bbc.co.uk. Retrieved [[February 14]], [[2007]].</ref> 

